{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018FaN943vsRFjtZixwcsqpF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Seeds 0, 1, 3, 42 work. Seed 2 still fails. Let me debug it.\n\nSeed 2: surface=[1.028, 1.158], block at cx=1.448, top=0.162. On surface: obs1 (top=0.264, cx=1.172) and obs3 (top=0.200, cx=0.999).\n\nWith block exclusion [1.448-0.100, 1.448+0.100]=[1.348, 1.548].\n\n\nI'm checking where obs1 can be deposited. With its width of 0.182, I need a half-width of 0.110. Testing x=0.15 against all obstacles—the surface, block, and other observations—none of them overlap, so that position works. Now I'm calculating obs1's final x-range after depositing it there.\n\nFor obs3, which is narrower at width 0.066, I'm scanning potential x positions to avoid overlaps. At x=0.15 it collides with obs1's deposited range. Moving to x=0.40 clears obs1 but hits obs0. At x=0.65 and x=0.70, obs3 still overlaps with obs0, so I need to keep testing further positions. Everything to the right gets blocked by that exclusion zone, so I need to focus on what's available to the left. Let me systematically check the lower x values to see where there's actually room.\n\nAt x=0.36, the dependent observation finally stops overlapping, but the primary observation still does. By x=0.37, I'm still hitting overlap with the primary observation. The key insight is that there's no gap between where the dependent observation ends (accounting for the half-width buffer) and where the primary observation begins—the clear range doesn't start until x=0.351.\n\nBut the primary observation's left edge minus its half-width puts the boundary at 0.307, creating a narrow window of only 0.044 units wide. My 0.05-step scan starting from 0.15 hits 0.30, 0.35, 0.40—none of which fall in that tight [0.307, 0.351] range. At x=0.35, I'm still barely overlapping the dependent observation, and by x=0.40, I'm back to overlapping the primary one. I'm missing a 